column168: Our driver was delivering diesel from our tanker to an above ground tank using a pump attached to our truck.  Upon connecting the hoses and fittings, the driver did not make sure the ears on the hose were properly secured.  The driver engaged the PTO to pump the product off of our tanker and within fifteen seconds our hose disconnected from the pump fitting and product was released into the immediate area.  The driver ran back around to the front of the truck and immediately shut off the pump.  It is estimated that approximately 80-100 gallons were released.  The product ran about sixty feet into a storm drain, which empties out into an on-site detention pond.  The pond had a significant amount of water in it and all of the product released was contained inside of the detention pond.  Spill pads and aborbent booms were used to help contain the product within the detention pond.  A vac truck was used to recapture the product from the detention pond and storm drain.
column169: We utilize locking ears on our pump hoses to prevent such incidents from occurring.  The driver knew that the ears on the hose he was using were not operating correctly and didn't report it to anyone to have them repaired.  He chose to continue using the hose even though the ears were not locking into place.  In addition, he did not make sure the ears were secured in a closed position before beginning the pump off.  The cause of the incident was human error.  The driver is being reprimanded with a suspension and will be retrained on the proper use of our equipment.

column168: Apparently another driver cut off the truck and trailer resulting in a hard braking incident that resulted in a load shift. The environmental contractor transferred the remaining product into drums, unloaded the trailer, clean up the impacted trailer floor and reloaded the trailer along with the three drums to continue for shipment. They then cleaned up the area of impacted asphalt beneath the trailer and secured the soil ditch line until utility locates could be obtained. Once obtained, excavation activities will take place. All waste generated was containerized and transported off site for disposal.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 4/1/2011 at 00:43 hrs.,  personnel at the CSXT Avon yard in Avon, IN, discovered PROX 31899, a residue tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, emitting an odor from the protective house area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Vertellus Specialties and IDEM, were notified via CHEMTREC  #2011-04-01-00005. Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device O ring was misaligned. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative Brian Hay 317-248-6573. Summit Environmental personnel removed the O ring cap, realigned the O ring and cleaned the valve assembly. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 413  NARRI Code: 2 (4+10+2) x (2+0) = 64
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 2, 2011 at 21:24 hours at the CSXT Low yard in Parkersburg, WV, personnel reported tank car GATX 50766, DOT 111A100W5, a load of Hydrochloric Acid Solution, was noted venting vapor from its top area. The car was isolated and Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. CHEMTREC #2011040200104, was notified and the shipper's representative, Mr. John Prince 270-395-6379,  advised shipper assistance to the scene was not forthcoming. On April 3, 2011 at 02:50 hours SPSI advised the frangible disc for the pressure relief vent was broken and the plug for the pressure relief vent "Quick Inspect" port was not in place, but rather dangling at the pressure releif vent assembly attached to a cable seal. The bottom threads of this plug were broken rendering this fitting improper. Mr. R. Anderson, Tetra Technologies, Parkersburg, WV advsied CSXT, that on April 3, 2011, he replaced the rupture disc, its gasket and "Quick Inspect" port rendering the car safe for transportation.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) =100

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liquid Valve
column168: Tank car AMCX 25813 in the railyard was reported leaking product from its top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was immediately notified to inspect AMCX 25813. The responder reported intact seal INEOS 127396 was removed from the valve housing cover to determine the source of the product leak. Detailed inspection revealed the leak source was the liquid valve's closure plug that was not tool tight. The responder tool tightened this closure plug (3/4 turn) ending this product release by 0118 hrs. CDT, 4/02/2011. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The pooled spillage at the base of the valves was absorbed by a sorbent pad. The small amount of spillage on the top shell near the valve housing area was wiped. No ground impact was observed. The valve housing cover was closed, but not immediately resealed, since this responder planned to recheck AMCX 25813 during daylight hours.  No further product leaks were detected during this latter inspection. The valve housing cover was closed and then sealed with seal BNSF Haz Mat 001266.  AMCX 25813's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2004 and next due in 2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. During a routine inspection of the trailer, by the Arizona Highway Patrol HAZMAT unit, it was discovered that a 250 gallon plastic tote of Tetramethylammonium Hydroxide Solution was leaking.  Less than 5 gallons of free product were released and impacted the plastic tote and the trailer floor.  The Arizona Highway Patrol HAZMAT Unit made an entry into the trailer and determined that the leaking tote had a loose bung. The Arizona Highway Patrol HAZMAT Unit applied a neutralizing compound to the free liquid and tightened the loose bung on the leaking tote.  The Arizona Highway Patrol HAZMAT Unit released the truck, and the truck continued onto its final destination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and was the result of a loose bung, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Chemical Logistics, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liquid Valve
column168: Tank car NATX 29215 entrained in an inbound BNSF train in the railyard was reported leaking product from its top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material was immediately notified. The responder reported intact seal inscribed as Tyden/Brammall X 165972 was removed to inspect fittings under the valve housing cover. The leak source was found to be the liquid valve that had its closure plug not tool tight. Also, the liquid valve's valve stem retainer nut behind this valve's operating handle was found loose. The responder tool tightened the liquid valve's closure plug (1/2 turn) and tightened the valve stem's retainer nut by 1454 hrs. CDT, 4/02/2011. Afterwards, no further product release was evident. The valve housing cover was closed and sealed with seal BNSF Haz Mat 001249. All spillage at the valve housing area and on the tank's side shell rapidly evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The transport truck driver connected the vapor recovery line from cargo tank to storage tank.  The driver connected the 90 degree coupling device to the storage tank fitting.  The driver connected down stream end of the unloading line to the 90 degree coupling.  The driver connected the upstream end of the unloading line to the cargo tank outlet.  The driver opened the cargo tank outlet valve.  The surge of fluid in the line causes the unloading line to "shake" until the line is completly full of product flowing downstream.  The "shake" movement at the downstream end of the line caused the unsecure connection at the 90 degree coupling inlet to become disconnected.  Product flowed freely from the open end of the unloading line until the driver closed the cargo tank outlet valve.
column169: This driver will be re-trained in the proper methods of unloading.  Special emphasis will be given to the procedural step known as "check your connections".  After attending retraining, this driver will be required to perform his duty under close supervision for a period of time.  This supervision will be documented with a report known as a Incident Prevention Observation (IPO.  The IPO will be retained in the driver's personnel file.    In addition, all drivers will be reminded to follow proper procedural steps while loading and unloading.  This reminder will be discussed at the next monthly safety meeting.

column168: Consignee states that they placed an order with the shipper for 3,000 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide. The shipper inadvertently loaded 3,800 gallons which was indicated on the shipper bill of lading. The driver arrived at the consignee, his paperwork was presented to the consignee, and he unloaded the material, put away his equipment and left the facility. At no time did anyone at the consignee mention any kind of a problem to the driver. Carrier was contacted the following day by the consignee Plant Supervisor who stated that they had had a spill of approximately 80 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide in a contained area and that his personnel had neutralized and cleaned up the spill. He stated that his receiving personnel had not adequately checked the paperwork when the driver arrived and that they had not stayed with the driver during the unloading process. He said that their receiving tank fed over into a secondary tank some distance away that did not have a high level alarm and it was this secondary tank that vented approximately 80 gallons of material into a contained area.
column169: Consignee must have their operations personnel carefully examine order confirmation from shipper for accuracy. Receiving personnel must follow their process and procedures to insure that all paperwork is correct before accepting delivery and remain with the driver to supervise the unloading process.

column168: On 04/12/2011 at 09:19 hrs., CSXT personnel on train Q69611 at mile post Z94 reported UTLX 900414, a loaded tank car of Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid, was leaking vapors from the top of the rail car, not from the regulating valve. The car was set out in the siding track and the shipper, Praxair, Inc., was notified thru CHEMTREC, report 2011-04-12-00084. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line was open and the plug was not in the valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mike Marshall - 716-879-7742. HEPACO removed the ice from around the valve and protective housing, closed the valve, reinserted the plug and the leak stopped. The car was then released for transportation to destination.     This incident did require a special switch move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report will not be required for this incident    Cause code: 117  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60      .
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 04/09/2011 at 1755 hrs., personnel in Manchester, GA discovered AR IX 1305, a loaded tank car of Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid, leaking from the dome area. The car was isolated and the shipper - Lined LLC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2011-04-09-00082. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk had activated. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative,  Eagle/SWS personnel monitored the railcar until the shippers technician responded from RESCAR to confirm the rupture disk condition. A new rupture disk was sent to RESCAR and the disk was replaced on Friday, April 15, 2011. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  An estimate of 50 gallons of product leaked from the car. The release started at 1755 hrs and the car was reported to have stopped venting at 0730 on April 10, 2011.    This incident did require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.     Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2 (5+1+0) x (3+0) = 36
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While at the UPRR Livonia, LA yard, tank car UTLX 202020 was observed to be leaking lading from beneath the combination housing and down the sides of the tank. Inspection by UPRR Haz Mat Manager T. M. Robinson revealed that the liquid eduction valve was slightly open and lading was leaking past the plug.  Robinson was assisted by a technician from response contractor Oil Mop Inc.  Initial attempts to close the valve were unsuccessful and tightening the plug did not stop the leak. After bleeding off the pressure in the tank, the liquid valve plug was removed and the valve opened to determine that there was no obstruction in the throat of the quarter turn ball valve.  The valve was then successfully closed and the plug reinstalled. Sorbent pads were used to remediate the spillage.

column168: BNSF intermodal facility personnel reported intermodal trailer FSTZ 883012 (that arrived earlier on a BNSF train) with dried and semi-dried yellow paint on the trailer's rear wheels, under frame and at the rear doorway threshold. FSTZ 883012 was deramped from its intermodal flatcar that it was riding upon and taken to the facility's containment area. The shipper was notified and sent a response contractor to investigate the leak source and remediate spillage. The contractor reported that one 5 gallon steel pail found towards the rear of the trailer's lading had buckled and incurred a bottom seam failure. The buckling was caused by heavy freight stacked atop the pail. The contractor cleaned the dried and semi-dried paint to an acceptable level and the lading within was adjusted.  Afterwards, FSTZ 883012 was released and out-gated from the BNSF intermodal facility.
column169: Ensure shipper adheres to the guidelines for acceptable intermodal loading configurations with the proper blocking and bracing in place.

column168: April 23, 2011: At approximately 11:30AM, CR crew FL01 noted tank car UTLX 205383, load, Isopropenylbenzene (3, PG III, UN 2303) leaking product from the top while car was under movement, only, during yard switching operations.  Car had been received on Friday, April 22, 2011 off the NS.  CR River Rouge Yardmaster had the crew isolate the car on the south end of Track #11 until it could be inspected/repaired.    Further inspection by emergency contractor Eagle/SWS (called by Conrail on behalf of shipper Sunoco) revealed one of six manway cover bolts not applied; one of six manway cover bolts not even finger tight; and remaining four of six manway cover bolts merely hand tight.  Original shipper's seal (recorded by Eagle/SWS, but not available at this submission) intact, was broken and manway cover opened to examine condition of manway cover gasket, finding no exceptions.  Manway cover closed and secured tool tight and car okayed to be forwarded onto original consignee, BASF, Wyandotte, MI.      It was reported that any product on sides of car at original time of incident had evaporated off the car and nothing was reported to have contacted the surrounding ground area.
column169: No additional comments.

column25: Green Plains Trade Group LLC by Tharaldson Ethanol
column168: Tank car CTCX 731633 was reported leaking in the railyard during normal switching activities. Movement was stopped and visual inspection revealed a product stain emanating from CTCX 731633's manway closure. Spillage on the side shell was evaporating and no ground impact was reported. CTCX 731633 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. No further release was evident when CTCX 731633 remained motionless. Contract responders inspected CTCX 731633 the morning of 4/10/2011 and reported finding all manway securement bolts tool tight. Further detailed inspection revealed the manway gasket was pinched and not providing a good closure seal. A new suitable manway gasket was installed and the manway cover was resecured by 0930 hrs. CDT, 4/10/2011. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact manway seal numbered 00153815 was replaced by seal PSC116093. Intact protective housing seal numbered 00153816 was replaced by seal PSC116098.  CTCX 731633's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Central Transport was carrying a tote of UN1210, printing ink in a trailer.  A loose cap caused the release of approxiamtely 20 gallons inside the trailer and onto the exit ramp of I-80 in Edon, OH.  An environmental contractor, ERS, was dispatched for cleanup.  They used a street sweeper to clean the roadway.  The impacted soil on the shoulder was excavated.  The product was collected from the inside of the trailer.  All impacted materials were containerized for transportation and disposal.  The contractor tightened the cap on the tote to ensure no future leak during transportation.

When unloading the totes, it was identified that 1 of the totes had a small release of material below the fittings on the valve. A contractor was called out to repair the valve. They repaired the leak with a welding putty and the tote was unloaded. No waste was generated from this cleanup.

column168: Tank car NATX 302246 in the railyard was reported leaking product onto its side shell from the top fitting area near the mounted pressure relief device (PRD). A BNSF mechanical responder inspected NATX 302246 and determined that it was safe to carefully move NATX 302246 to the facility's containment area/pit. A response contractor was called and inspected NATX 302246 in the containment pit. All seals were intact and all fittings were secure. The PRD was functioning as intended; but expelled product which is indicative of an overfilled condition. Inspection of the product outage via the manway determined that NATX 302246 was overfilled. Shipper arranged for product reduction and on 4/07/2011 approximately 1500 gallons was transferred into a tank truck without further incident. Spillage on the side shell of NATX 302246 evaporated. Afterwards, the response contractor cleaned the contents in the containment pit and delivered captured liquid to the railyard's waste treatment facility for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings; as well as, the appropriate product outages for expected ambient temperatures.

column168: During a walkthrough of the facility, the Terminal Manager noticed an employee disconnecting an elbow connection from the belly valve of a railcar after it was empty. When the employee removed the product hose, the product that was left in the hose spilled into the spill pan and the ground around the spill pan. There were pans under the railcar during the unloading however, before the hose disassembly occurred the pans were removed. Fellow teammates assisted to make sure as much product as possible was contained in the spill pan. An absorbent pad was used to contain the rest of the product that contacted the concrete. A total of 3.5 gallons was captured in the spill pan and with the absorbent pad.
column169: All employees were re-trained on the procedures for connecting elbow connections and product hoses. Terminal management and EHS staff have began conducting random inspections of the offloading proces sto ensure all proceures are being followed as required by the site specific procedures.

column168: A driver was performing a routine post trip inspection in the yard of the ten day storage facility.  He noticed a small leak inside the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A 330 gallon tote tank was found to be leaking from the top closure.  The closure device was malfunctioning.  The material was transferred into poly drums and the spilled material was cleaned up.  No material reached the pavement.  The absorbent pads used to clean the trailer were placed into the drums with the material.  The remainder of the totes were inspected and found to have a different closure.  The load then continued without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The generator was notified of the incident and stated they had no more of this type totes in their possession and would not be using them in the future.  The driver who picked up the shipment was questioned and stated he had carefully inspected the totes and they were not leaking at the time of pickup.

column168: During a routine check of the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a flex bin was noticed to be wet on the bottom.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, it was found that a small amount of material had leaked through the liner, through the box and onto the pallet.  The material was transferred into salvage drums.  No material reached the dock floor, only the cardboard and the wooden pallet were affected.  The state of Illinois Emergency Management authority was notified and assigned incident number H20110411.
column169: The generator was contacted and instructed how to properly load flex bin containers.  The bin had shown no signs of leaking when picked up.

column168: Tank car TILX 190502 was reported dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area during normal switching operations in the railyard. TILX 190502 was isolated in the railyard with a receptacle placed under its BOV to catch product drips. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected TILX 190502 finding the bottom operated BOV operating valve not pinned in the closed position. No shipper seals were present. The responder closed the valve by repositioning the operating handle to the closed position and secured it by 1950 hrs. PDT, 4/16/2011. Seal BNSF 06157922 was applied. Afterwards, the product drips from around the tool tight bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) ceased. The BOC was not removed for BOC gasket inspection. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Tank car TILX 318499 in the railyard was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure. TILX 318499 was carefully moved to and isolated at the facility's repair track location. No additional product leakage was observed during this movement and no active leak was detectable when TILX 318499 remained motionless. No ground impact from spillage was reported. The preliminary BNSF inspection of TILX 318499 revealed all six manway securement bolts were tool tight and the shipper seal at the manway was intact. The nearby loader of TILX 318499 (NuStar Energy) was notified and arranged for a contract responder to investigate and correct the cause of the manway closure product release. On 4/19/2011, the contract responder reported that the manway gasket applied was misaligned and not properly seated in the gasket groove on the bottom side of the manway lid. The responder properly repositioned the undamaged manway gasket and resecured the manway securement bolts. Seal BNSF 06160608 was applied to the manway. Spillage on TILX 318499's side shell dried/evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

A response contractor inspected TILX 110393 finding the installed 135 psig frangible disc had ruptured. The responders replaced this blown rupture disc with a suitable 165 psig frangible disc. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Spillage on the tank shell was neutralized with a caustic solution. No ground impact was detected.

Approx. 0.5 miles South of SR307 in Tunkhannock Twp, Wyoming County, PA, truck drifted onto right shoulder of paved highway and upon correcting to return to the pavement the right rear of the truck pulled to the right causing impact with rock cliffs at edge of right shoulder resulting in rupture of rear compartment. Damage to the tank began at mid-tank as an indentation/scratch on passenger-side tank shell and continued to the back of tank where it caused an 8" separation of the tank shell from end-cap resulting in leak.  Driver checked right rear-view mirror after impact and noticed fuel leaking from tank.  Driver proceeded approx. 0.5 miles to a "safe haven", stopped truck, called emergency personnel and contained the spill.  Tunkhannock Twp. Fire & Rescue, PA Dept. of Environmental Protection, and Wyoming County EMA attended the scene, contained the leak, cleaned up immediate area, and emptied tank compartment of all contents.  A spill rememdiation team was called in to clean scene in its entirety and company truck was returned to company yard.

On April 21, 2011 at approximately 1415 hours a Linden Bulk Transportation truck was receiving a load of Diethanolamine (DEA) at IMTT when the IMTT Operator discovered liquid coming out of the bottom valve of the trailer.  The IMTT Operator immediately shut down the pump and closed the loading valves.  The IMTT Operator went to the back of the trailer compartment and noticed that both the internal and external valves were left open.  The IMTT Operator immediately closed both valves and notified his supervisor.  EQ Terminal Services was dispatched to the area and cleaned up the affected areas of the trailer compartment and loading rack.  The clean up operation was completed by 1545 hours and the loading operation resumed without further incident.  The National Response Center and US Coast Guard were notified of the incident due to the release being in excess of the reportable quantity which is 13 gallons.
column169: As part of IMTT's ISO-9000 procedure there is a check list that requires that the IMTT Operator and Linden driver verify that all unused outlet valves are closed prior to loading.  In this case this procedure was not followed.  The IMTT Operator was counseled and re-trained and appropriate disciplinary action was taken.

column168: A BNSF crew in the process of spotting consignee railcars at the Goodyear Tire and Rubber plant shoved tank car UTLX 805169 over a track derail (leading to the industrial track) that the crew failed to position to its non-derailing position. UTLX 805169 derailed on its side and was not compromised nor leaking any of its hazardous material contents. The fire department and county sheriff representatives on scene initiated a precautionary evacuation of residences within a 1/2 mile radius of the derailment site. Also, Texas Highway 124 that runs adjacent and parallel to the Goodyear plant was closed to through traffic between Smith and Gaulding roads (a distance of approximately 1 1/2 miles). Impacted Highway 124 traffic was detoured onto nearby U.S. I-10. The Goodyear plant did not evacuate. The residential evacuation was lifted at approximately 2045 hrs. CDT, 4/15/2011. Highway 124 was fully reopened at approximately 0200 hrs. CDT, 4/16/2011 after UTLX 805169 was uprighted intact and rerailed at 0130 hrs. CDT, 4/16/2011.

column168: A Covenant tractor trailer experienced an apparent load shift.  This caused two pieces of cargo to release product inside the trailer.  1.  A 55-gallon drum of UN2922, Corrosive Liquids, Toxic NOS, 8, PG II   2.  A 5-gallon bucket of UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, NOS, 8, PG II   Approximately 2 gallons of product was released from these containers.    An environmental contractor, H2O, arrived on site for cleanup.  They overpacked the damaged drum for disposal.  The leaking bucket had a loose cap after being tipped.  The contractor confirmed that the cap was reattached and safe for transport.  All impacted cargo was wiped clean. The trailer was cleaned, neutralized, secured, and re-packed for proper transportation.

column168: On April 28, 2011, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU435072-4 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Broken Component or Device
column168: On 04/13/2011 at 03:20 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon yard discovered ETCX 22017, a loaded tank car of Diethyl Ether, emitting an odor from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Equistar Chemicals LP was notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-04-13-00023. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the thermometer well cap to be less than hand tight, emitting odor and the bottom outlet valve packing nut was less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative. Summit Environmental personnel secured the thermometer cap and the shipper contracted Rescar to secure the bottom outlet valve. The leak was stopped and the car was released for transport.     This incident did require several special switching moves.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause codes: 525, 535, 547

Please note, BAX Global, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only.    According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While staged in the dangerous goods area at the Swanton, OH HUB there was a shipment of two (2), fiberboard boxes containing two (2), Perfumery product glass bottles of which, one (1) glass bottle was damaged.  Upon further investigation, one (1) glass bottle was damaged due to improper handling or improper preparation for transportation.  Approximately, one (1)liter of product was released and all contained to the fiberboard box.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel used gloves and two (2) plastic bags to clean up the spill.  One (1), thirty (30) gallon steel drum of waste was generated including the damaged product and cleanup materials.  The thirty (30) gallon steel drum was returned to the shipper.  The remaining shipment was forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: BAX Global, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was unloading at a customer location. The driver did not properly tighten the fitting prior to unloading. While unloading the driver noticed the fitting come off of drop tube. The driver was standing next to the belly valve and immediately shut off the flow of product but approximately 12-18 gallons spilled onto the concrete. A drain was located about 15 feet from the spill and a small amount reached the drain but once the drain was tested it was determined that there was no product in the drain tube. There was an area of 5-8 feet on concrete that was stained from the spill. SWS was called in to dig up and replace the asphalt.
column169: Upon investigating the incident, it appears as though the driver was in a hurry and failed to follow correct unloading procedure, assuring that the fitting was tightly attached to the drop tube. The driver will be placed back into training and will have followm up incident prevention observation conducted on him.

column168: Driver hooked up tractor to trailer at base in Shakopee, MN.  Checked for proper coupling by pulling against trailer after latched.  Drove to Roseville MN and loaded load.  Left terminal for destination and after making the cloverleaf from NB I35W to WB I694 had the trailer uncouple from the tractor.  The nose of the trailer hit the ground and sheared off the landing gear, front compartment pipe to discharge valve, and crunched the pump and piping thats used for above ground tanks pump off.  The trailer skidded for 100 yards on the concrete which ignited the gasoline that was in the front compartment pipe.  Driver called 911 and reported to highway patrol and fire department.  The fire burned out after product was gone.  Local fire department sprayed foam on pipe and internal valve to keep from re-igniting.
column169: Kelley Fuels, Inc. installed heavy duty 5th wheel with secondary locking mechanism onto truck.  Kelley Fuels, Inc also had representative from Holland give tutorial to all drivers on latching practices. Kelley Fuels, Inc. added new tools to own shop to check for pin and plate wear.  As of this time there is not a determination of what caused the decoupling.  These were the steps we took as a company to verify that what we were doing was to the best of our capability.

According to the information obtained, during unloading a cardboard box was found to be tipped over and soaked with gasoline. Service Manager Wade Hampton responded to perform the cleanup. Service Manager Hampton performed an investigation, and determined that the cardboard box contained a small engine which had not been completely drained of gasoline. Mr. Hampton removed the box from the terminal and allowed it to air dry, after which the box containing the small engine was placed in the terminal hazmat holding area. The shipment was picked up by the Consignee.

column168: On April 1, 2011, during routine receipt inspection of rail conveyances with radioactive waste, the Energy Solutions inspectors identified a rail car (serial number ENVX206247) was leaking liquid through a drain cap. The leak rate was approximately 1 drip every 10 seconds. The leak was immediately secured and the rail car was moved into a licensed facility within the controlled area of the Clive Facility. Radiological surveys of the rail car and rail track identified no radioactive contamination. The National Response Center and shipper were notified. Further inspections were performed on April 7, 2011. The drain cap was removed and the liquid in the rail car was allowed to flow into a sump. Approximately 1400 gallons was drained from the rail car. The waste material in the railcar was metal debris. The total volume of the rail car is 6275 cuft and the volume of the waste material in the rail car was 5000 cuft.The shipper was interviewed during the time period of the rail car inspection. The shipper indicated that the rail car was loaded during a rain storm but, did not know that a significant amount of liquid collected in the rail car.The rail car unloaded on April 16, 2011. There were no further discrepancies identified.
column169: Our Quality Assurance Department has requested a corrective action plan from the shipper. Most of our shippers use absorbent material on the bottom of their containers and inspect the drain closures.

column168: After pulling railcars from shipper's facility (Bayer Corp.), the BNSF train crew reported a strong residue product odor emanating from entrained tank car PPGX 1426. These railcars were setout in an isolated area at Eldon Jct. station (UPRR Baytown Subdiv.). BNSF and contract responders inspected PPGX 1426. An audible vapor hiss was detected as responders approached PPGX 1426. Contract responders reported finding the A-end liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not tool tight. Responders closed the liquid valve by 2309 hrs. CDT, 4/28/2011 which ended the vapor hiss and the odor dissipated thereafter. Further inspection of all other valves revealed that they were 1/2 turn from being fully closed. After all valves were closed, all valve closure plugs were removed, cleaned, threads retaped and plugs reapplied to a tool tight condition. Intact valve housing cover seal PPG 012741 was replaced by seal OMI 652626.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: NARRATIVE:   On 4/8/11 at approximately 9:30am, an estimated 50 gallons of hydrogen peroxide were released when a metered pump failed.  The release was contained on the asphalt and did not impact any drainage.  The federal reportable quantity threshold of 1000 pounds was not met however; the release was required to be reported to the State.     AWARENESS ITEM:   1. The meter was set at 4000 gallons but overflowed at 3903 gallons.   2. The pump and meter involved in this release is Shipper owned.   3. The pump has been in use at the terminal since 2003.  The meter has only needed to be changed out four times in that time period.   4. The meter was changed out two weeks prior to release.   5. Meter was reset at the beginning of this transfer and appeared to be in functioning order.   6. This was the first peroxide load of the day.   7. Severe weather at the terminal caused a power line at the end of the terminal to ground out which could have possibly shorted out the meter’s program board, per discussion with Shipper and TRANSFLO.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION:   1. Shipper will change meter out.   2. The trailer fittings will be fitted for an outage alarm as a back-up.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A passing westbound BNSF train crew reported an entrained tank car UTLX 205091 in an eastbound BNSF train on main track was leaking product onto its side shell. The eastbound train was stopped on main track awaiting inspection from summoned BNSF responders. The BNSF responders reported finding UTLX 205091's liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not applied.  The responders positioned the liquid valve's operating handle to the closed position which ended any further product release. The liquid valve's closure plug was applied and tool tightened. The valve housing cover was closed and pinned, but not resealed. Rainy conditions during the response prevented tank shell spillage from being wiped dry. A hydrocarbon degrading microbial product was applied to the ground impact area observed. BNSF environmental responders will perform additional spill impact area inspections along the main track in the near future.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 04/08/2011 at approximately 14:10PM, CN local train NR93091-08 derailed two railcars during a low speed shoving move on the CN / CSXT East Wye, Effingham, IL. One tank car, GATX 10817 (L/ Methyl Methacrylate Monomer, Stabilized)  derailed on it's side. No product was released, no tank damage noted. There was minor damage to the protective housing cover.  Local Fire Department and Hazmat Team responded, relocating employees from one nearby business to another portion of their warehouse. It was later learned that two other businesses within a half mile of the incident scene were evacuated or closed early due to the derailment. A recon was conducted, no confirmed product release noted. The Fire Department IC released the Hazmat Team at 17:30PM.  CN's response team arrived at approximately 18:00PM and confirmed no product release took place, condensation was noted on the manway and associated valves were due to the products temperature.  GATX 10817 was uprighted at 20:20PM and rerailed at 21:10PM.  Evacuation lifted at approximately 20:30PM.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Branch Manager, Ken Cole received a call from Southern Regional Manager about a leak at Gorman Apopka store around 1415.  Branch Manager called the driver, Nathan Glen Tolman, and was informed that he had delivered sodium hypochlorite and purged his line prior to disconnect.  However, the driver failed to disconnect his line, resulting in the fracture of the customer above ground storage tank loading hose, before pulling away from the customer location.  Bleach drained from the customer loading hose onto the ground and parking lot.  The driver informed us that he along with the Gorman employees were washing down the area and neutralizing the spill.  Branch Manager went to the customer area and on speaking with the Gorman manager determined that 75 gallons had leaked out.
column169: Driver, Nathan Tolman was written up for not following our SOP in notifing dispatch immediately of a spill and for failing to disconnect his hose before leaving the customers area and for failing to take pictures.  Driver also went through retraining on unloading procedures.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. arrived at the Bristol CT plant for offloading and disposal. During offloading approximatly 4 ounces of liquid spilled when the containers top popped off. Facility personnel  clean-up the spilled product from the van trailer (no product leaked from the van) and sent the drum immediatly to disposal. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The driver who accepted the waste was re-trained in proper container selection and all drivers at his service center were spoken to about proper container selection by the local general manager.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES) was transporting a bulk load of filter cake from a customer located in Fort Lupton, CO destined for Clean Harbor's Deer Trail disposal facility located in Deer Trail, CO.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at CHES’ Kimball Nebraska facility to obtain rest before continuing on to the intended waste management facility. The bulk load contained approximately 25 cubic yards of filter cake in a roll-off box equipped with a soft top tarp system.      At the time of the accident, the driver was heading southbound on Highway 71 between Mile Markers 210-211, approximately 8 miles North of Stoneham, Colorado, when the truck went of the road on the west side.  The tractor and roll off trailer came to rest upright off the road and during the time the driver attempted to recover and return to the roadway, the roll-off box broke free from the trailer and flipped upside down depositing the filter cake in a pile that measured approximately 108’ by 33’ including thinly spread material.  The bulk of the material was deposited in a pile that was about three times the footprint of the roll-off box. The material released was a dry solid and as such was contained on the dirt and grass land abutting the highway.  Please note there were no waterways or storm drains impacted by this incident. The power unit and trailer did not roll-over as a result of the incident.      Emergency services were immediately dispatched to the scene as were representatives from the CO state Police, Emergency Services and an internal Clean Harbor's response Team.  Upon arrive, the driver was removed from the scene and treated/released with minor injuries.  The spill scene was secured and a response action was initiated to remove the vehicle and initiate clean-up activities.  IN addition, all required notifications were made to the US EPA, Colorado State Police, The Colorado Department of Transportation and the Colorado Department of Public Health.    Over the next 2 days, clean -up and remediation activities were conducted under the direction of Clean Harbors Environmental Services and routine updates were communicated to the applicable State Agencies.  In addition to the recovery of all spilled material, Clean Harbors Generated approximately 18 cubic yards of additional spill debris that was properly containerized and sent for disposal to a full permitted waste management facility.  Prior to departing the scene, the impacted surface area was backfilled with a sufficient amount of soil to return the area to the appropriate grade.
column169: During the initial investigation, it was determined that the primary cause of the release was attributed to the abnormally high wind activity.  It is believed that the vehicle encountered a gust of wind that pushed the vehicle towards the soft shoulder.  The driver attempted to correct the path of the vehicle but was unable to recover resulting in the vehicle catching the soft shoulder.  The force of the impact with the soft shoulder caused the roll-off container to violently shift allowing the front securement devices to fail resulting in the box coming off the roll-off frame.  Though we believe environmental factors were the primary cause of the event, the driver involved in this event, along with his local peers will be retrained on proper load securement requirements so as to insure that each container is properly blocked and braced during transportation.

column168: DRIVER PULLED INTO FLYING J FOR FUEL, SMELLED ODOR AT REAR OF TRUCK, COULD NOT SEE PROBLEM, CALLED RDW SAFETY DEPT, WE HAD DRIVER PULL TO REAR OF TRUCK STOP, DON PROTECTIVE GEAR, OPEN REAR OF TRAILER; DRIVER COULD NOT DETERMINE SOURCE OF ODOR; WALKED TO FRONT OF TRAILER-REAR OF TRUCK NOTICED DARK LIQUID HAD DRIPPED ONTO DRIVE TIRES ON LEFT SIDE.  RDW SAFETY AND DRIVER PULL OUT SPILL KIT AND PLACE DRIP PADS UNDER AND AROUND TIRES TO PREVENT LIQUID FROM SPLASHING ONTO GROUND; DRIVER STATED DRIP WAS INTERMITTENT AND VERY MINIMAL.  DRIVER SEGREGATED ARE, KEPT OTHERS AWAY IN A CLAM MANNER.  RDW SAFETY CALLED OH EPA AND NRC.  CONTRACTED ER NUMBER ON MANIFEST-HAD CH CLEAN-UP CREW DISPATCHED TO SCENE.  AS A PRECAUTION CH (CLEAN HARBORS CLEAN-UP FOREMAN) HAD DRIVER NOTIFY TRUCK STOP MANAGER TO CALL LOCAL 911 AND REPORT. TRUCK STOP WAS EVACUATED AND ER PERSONNEL ESCORTED TRUCK/TRAILER TO HEBRON OH CLEAN HARBORS WERE TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED AND RELOADED ONCE LEAKING DRUM IDENTIFIED AND PLUGGED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING.  DRUM HAD BEEN PINCHED WHILE LOADING, 3 OTHER HAD LOOSE COVERS (RING NOT TIGHT). LOOSE RINGS TIGHTENED, PLUGGED DRUM OVERPACKED, PRODUCT RELOADED AND SECURED IN TRAILER 8029.  DRIVER PERFORMED WELL.  FOLLOWED EMERGENCY GUIDELINES, STAYED CALM AND PREVENTED POSSIBLE INJURY TO OTHERS.  SINCE SOURCE OF ODOR WAS NOT DISCOVERED RIGHT AWAY, KEEPING OTHERS AWAY AND USING PROTECTIVE GEAR WAS RIGHT COURSE TO FOLLOW.
column169: EVEN THOUGH LEAK WAS MINOR, PROPER LOADING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE LEAKAGE.  SHIPPER MUST BE AWARE OF LOOSE COVERS AND RINGS AND EXERCISE CAUTION SO AS NOT TO PINCH DRUMS WHEN LOADING.  THIS MATERIAL WAS AT THE FRONT OF A PRE-LOADED TRAILER AND DRIVER'S CANNOT ACCESS WHEN PICKING UP AND SECURING THE LOAD.

TERMINAL OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR JUAN VALLEJO RESPONDED AND CONDUCTED AND INVESTIGATION, AND DETERMINED THAT THE BOX CONTAINED EIGHT(8) 16-OUNCES BOTTLES OF CRYSTAL OR GLASS COMPOSITION WITHOUT ANY INNER PACKAGING.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS APPARENTLY DAMAGED  DURING  THE FREIGHT SCREENING PROCESS, RELEASING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE BOTTLE.  TERMINCAL OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR VALLEJO PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  QUANTUM MARKETING WAS CONTACTED ON APRIL 25, 2001 FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET RECEIVED BY SCHENKE, INC. SHOWS THE PRODUCT AS BEING CLASSIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS, CLAS S8, UN2735.  THE DAMAGED BOTTLE AND THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN PICKED UP BY THE SHIPPER

column168: TUESDAY APRIL 5, 2001 2020: RELEASE OF MONCHLOROACETIC ACID (MCA) DISCOVERED BY HESR STAFF (GREG MASON) AT THE HESR-DURAND YARD BENEATH TANK CAR DOWX 40022.  THE FREEZING TEMPERTURE OJF MCAA IS 63F AN DAMBIENT TEMPERATURES HAD BEEN NO HIGHER THAN 30-40F.  THE RELEASE REPORTEDLY APPEARED AS A MOUND OF WHITE MATERIAL DESCRIBED AS THE SIZE OF A DISWASHER BENEATH THE PARKED TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS IN THE SOUTH YARD ON THE S2 TRACK.  THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN FILLED INMIDLAND AT THE DOW PLANT AND TRANSPORTED FIRST TO THE HESR-WENONA YARD IN BAY CITY BEFORE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT DURAND YARD.   HESR CONTRACTED YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP (YOUNG'S ) TO PROVIDE CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP SERVICES.  YOUNG'S CONTACT IS GARY BRANNOCK 810-789-7155.  YOUNG'S MOBILIZED TO THE SITE WEDNESDAY APRIL 6, 2011 BEGININNG AT 0100.  THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO A DIFFERENT PART OF THE DURAND YARD (SHORTBELT TRACK IN THE WEST YARD)  FOR ISOLATION AND TRANSLOADING OPERATIONS.  YOUNG'S PLACED A RECEPTACLE BENEATH THE LEAKING CAR TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL RELEASED MCAA.  ADDITIONALLY, DUE TO FORECASTED PRECIPITATION, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ADJACENT TO THE PRODUCT PILE AT TRAC S2 TO CAPTURE POTENTIAL RUN OFF AS MCAA IS MISCRIBLE IN WATER.   YOUNGS'S RECOVERED THE SPILLED SOLID MATERIAL AT THE S2 TRACK INTO 55-GALLON POLY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AND CONTAINMENT.  A TOTAL OF 12 POLY DRUMS WERE GENERATED.  AMEC EARTH & ENVIRONMENTAL , INC.  (MIKE DELONG, 810-220-8941) MOBILZED TO THE SITE ON WEDNESDAY APRIL 6, 2011 AT 0850.  AMEC DOCUMENTED AND PROVIDED OVERSIGHT OF RESPONSE ACTIVITIES (SEE ATTACHED CONTINUATION SHEETS)

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: The Tractor-Trailer(Tanker) Rig was traveling West on I-395.  It exited onto the Rightside Exit No. 2 towards Route 202 towards Hampden.  While on the Off Ramp making a sharp Left-Hand Turn, the Rig left the road on the right side crossing the right side shoulder, crashing through the guardrail, down the grassy slope into a small gulley and rolled over.  The Driver was able to self-rescue and exit the cab through the damaged windshield.  He was able to walk back onto the road, call 911 Services and walked up to the Emergency Responders.  He was treated on scene EMS for cuts and taken to hospital for test and was diagnosed with a concussion and released that day.  The tanker shell was cracked appox. five(5) feet oppening the front two(2) compartments, and was the source of the released fuel.  The rear three(3) compartments had a hole drilled for pumping out product.  All Compartments had product pumped out into a rescue trailer; totaling 5,550 USG.  Recovered spilled fuel was 130 USG from a drip pan and vaccum pump by outside clean-up contractor.
column169: 1.  Company aide Safety Standowns(Post Incident) Lesson Learned Trainings & Meetings were called and conducted for all Bulk Fuel Delivery Drivers.  The DOT FMSCA "Cargo Tank Driver Rollover Prevention" Video was shown.    2.  The Company Accident Review Committee met to review the accident and emergency response.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On the morning of or about 28 April 2011, our warehouseman was checking in freight  from the Bethel (BET) station and noticed a plastic tote of a declared UN2794, Battery, wet, filled with acid, 8, III with a hazardous material handling label that looked to be an off color to what the DOT Chart 14 shows. This tote was banded to a pallet and had sufficient absorbent material to absorb the entire contents in the event of a spill or leak.    In our internal investigation, we found that the BET station agent, whose training is  current, had failed to thoroughly inspect the shipment. The documentation, marking and labeling was correct and was noted on the checksheet that is used for accepting hazardous material shipments, however it was the packaging that was improper. This battery was placed into the plastic tote filled with vermiculite and banded to a pallet. The battery was not packed in a fiberboard box inside the plastic tote.    This freight had already flown from BET to ANC.    Immediate actions were to obtain photographs of the improperly packaged hazardous  material (attached) and begin an internal investigation. We also have embargoed  hazardous material shipments from this station until we can be assured that all steps are taken to minimize our exposure to improperly prepared hazardous material shipments.     According to the statements from the BET station, this shipment was declared but was not scrutinized as thoroughly as it should have been and it appears that some assumptions were made.    Below is the response given by the BET station agent regarding this shipment.    -------------------------------------    Thank You and Take Care.  Heather A Pike  Bethel Station Manager  907-444-7811  Sent from Samsung Mobile    Heather,      This email is in refrence to the hazmat shipment for LKDS that was shipped out of the Bethel station. I do remember this shippment. I remember the haz-dec being correct. I remember filling out the checklist. I remember needing to go out and re sticker the shippment as far as haz- mat labels goes. I dont, however, remember if i actually did that or not. I do remember that the battery was in a white plastic tub that was eventually banded to a pallet. I was under the assumption that the plastic tub was an acceptable type of container. Now, i do not have any of the paperwork in front of me at this time to be able to refrence it, do to the fact that i am on my vacation on the east coast. Please let me know if you would like to know anything else. Have a great day.    Russell Lamont Jr.  Station Agent  Northern Air Cargo - BETHEL  US +1 9075434155 Call
column169: On 29 April 2011, Northern Air Cargo placed a backhaul hazardous material embargo on  the BET station. This embargo will be in effect until a new procedure can be  implemented which we are working on which will be completed in the near future that  will affect not only BET, but all scheduled destinations that we service in Alaska.     We will be contacting all stations in an effort to enhance awareness to all of the aspects of a hazardous material shipment including the new procedures to be in place as soon as possible. Some of these awareness points are; looking for undeclared hazardous materials, ensuring the shipments that do contain hazardous materials, that they are scrutinized thoroughly, the importance of using the checklists provided and if there are any questions to ensure that these questions are asked and answered. We want to ensure that every agent involved in the acceptance and handling of hazardous materials do not exceed their training and resort to assumptions.

column168: On April 27, 2011, R&L Carriers contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) of a tote which was leaking to a secondary containment of the tote.  ERTS dispatched United States Environmental Services (USES) to the site to transfer the product to a new container and perform any necessary remediation.  USES personnel arrived on site and transferred the product from the damaged tote and collected the material from the secondary containment to be sent back to the shipper.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 80 eastbound, driver swerved to avoid a third party vehicle, which caused tote to break away from restraining straps on trailer, and fall to the roadway.  Entire contents of the 500 gallon poly tote were released to the asphalt roadway and soil within the median.  Alabama Department of Environmental Management (ALDEM) was contacted, and responded to the site, along with Alabama Department of Transportation (ADOT).  One (1) eastbound lane of Highway 80, and one (1) westbound lane of Highway 80 were shut down as a result of the accident.  United States Environmental Services (USES) of Alabaster, Alabama was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Working at the direction of ALDEM and ADOT, USES neutralized the phosphoric acid on the asphalt roadway, and used a granular sorbent to recover residual product.  Neutralized product and granular absorbent material were swept to the roadside, and stockpiled, pending excavation of soils.  USES returned to the site during daylight hours to excavate the impacted soil from the median, which was containerized into rolloff boxes, along with spent absorbents, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  Site was backfilled and restored to preexisting condition.  There were no injuries or exposurse reported, as a result of the release.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: Flange on discharge pipe spool was mild steel, welded to stainless. Mild steel is incompatible with lading. Pipe spool was not original and source is unknown to owner. When internal valve was opened, leakage was immediately noticed and valve was shut. Leaked material was caught in plastic bucket. All-stainless spool pipe assembly was fabricated at tank shop and transported to consignee, repaired on-site. Unloading commenced without further incident. See attached:    Incident Summary    Date of incident: 04-08-2011  Completed by: Douglas Carothers Incident Recorded: 04-08-2011  Brief description:  HNO3 Release from 407 Tank Trailer    Spill      Accident Near Miss Other   Injury(ies): N/A   Replacement   or repairs    necessary? Associated              cost: $  Property damages:              Total:_________    Description:     04-08-2011 Driver arrives at El Dorado Chemical Co. in Es Dorado, AR at ~22:00, spotted vehicle in loading area. Unloading hose was connected and preparation for transfer of Nitric acid begun. Internal valve was opened hydraulically. Immediately Nitric Acid began leaking from flange of discharge line (spool pipe).     Internal valve closed, container placed under spool pipe flange to contain Nitric Acid, driver notifies Action Resources, Inc dispatcher and ER coordinator Theresa Posey at ~22:20, Theresa Posey notified TX terminal Mgr. Calvin Lewis at ~ 22:30.    Driver determines location of leak to be 10mm-15mm hole in welded joint between spool tube and flange.    TX terminal mechanic Rick Bellamy has replacement part fabricated at Brenner Tank shop in Houston and departs Houston for El Dorado. Arrives El Dorado Nitrogen, Co. at ~ 15:00, 04-09-2011 and installs replacement part, stays on site until transfer is complete and departs ~ 18:30, 04-09-2011.    Estimated volume released:    5 – 7  gallons per Action Resources, Inc. driver   15-20 gallons per El Dorado Chemical Co. personnel      RQ Release No RQ HNO3 = 1,000 lbs.   [8.34 x 1.41 = 11.76 lbs/gal x 20 gal. = 235 lbs.]                    Root cause and corrective actions report      HNO3 release:        Procedures     • Chemtrec not notified (by Action Resources, Inc personnel, release on El Dorado site).    Equipment    • Failure of weld between flange and spool pipe determined to be dissimilar metals joined by weld. Flange was fabricated from some grade of mild steel and welded to stainless spool pipe. This determination was made by applying a magnet to the flange and the spool pipe. The flange is magnetically attractive while the stainless spool pipe is not. Type 316 austenitic Stainless Steel is not normally magnetic and can only be made slightly so by cold-working or machining. This will cause a very slight transformation of a small portion of the austenitic to ferritic or martenitic stainless steel, which can be very weakly attracted to a magnetic field.  •   Tank #C7243 was leased from Jack Olsta Co. Houston Terminal Mgr, Calvin Lewis, c
column169: Action Resources, Inc. has begun inspecting all flanges in acid service with a magnet on the assumption that almost all 316SS is non-magnetic.    It is beleived that a previous customer of the lessor performed an unauthorized repair with improper materials.

column168: The accident took place approximately 4 miles from Richie Farms location on FM 468 West near Cotulla, Tx. IP wasdriving truck # 25625 when coming around the curve felt trailer sway, saw oncoming traffic flash lights moved over tothe right of the lane. At that point right tire dropped off shoulder and was corrected back on the road at which pointtrailer began to slide in the ditch and went over on its side. IP was transported by ambulance to Dilley, TX where hewas halo flighted to San Antonio for X ray and observation IP suffered partial separated shoulders on both arms andabrasion to left temple. IP was treated and released.The driver of unit 25625 notified the Alice district office that he had been involved in an accident at 7:40 AM. TheLaredo DPS office was notified as well as Emergency Medical Services who transported the driver to Dilly, Texasand then on to San Antonio by halo flight. Those at the scene used absorbent materials and diked earth to stop therun off of the spilled material. Eagle SWS was contacted and arrived on site to commence clean up activities.Note: The Weatherford unit 25625 was also transporting the following product:7 IBC's containing (Combustible Liquid, n.o.s., (Diesel Fuel Solution),3, UN1993,PGIII. Total Quantity released 2,310gallons.L_

THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS PUMPING JET FUEL OUT OF THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK. WE WERE PUMPING JET FUEL OUT OF ONE TANK ON THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY AND MOVING IT TO ANOTHER TANK ON THE SAME PROPERTY.
column169: KAG WEST, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: Driver was connected with 2- 2" hoses to customers tank from the trailer. As the driver turned on the pump, the connection between the 2 hoses started leaking at the camlock. When driver shut down the pump and cleared the line, he noticed that the gasket in the camlock fitting was bent and not sealing properly. He replaced with a new one and reconnected and finished offloading. Approx 1-2 gallons was lost in the containment area of the plant. The supervisor advised our driver that they would take care of the release.
column169: Driver was issued a written warning and sent for remedial training and also put on 6 months probation.

column168: During a roll-by train inspection, CN Engineering Department employees noted a strong odor coming from the 30th car in train, DTTX 742443, portable tank UTCU 480084 (L, ETHYL ACRYLATE, STABILIZED). The railcar was set out and isolated at the Pokegama Yard, Superior, WI. All appropriate departments notified. CNs response team responded noting vapors coming from the portable tanks manway area. Manway seal intact and the bolts were tool tight. Upon further inspection, the manway cover gasket was noted to be deteriorated, allowing product vapors to escape. New manway gasket applied and properly secured. Leak stopped, portable tank released for movement.

column168: The hose connection piece used to unload the railcar into totes failed.  The railcar did not have a safety valve on the flange, and our safety valve was above the breakage point.  Once this connection broke, material was forced through the flange due to the railcar being pressurized.  The air being fed into the railcar for pressurizing was stopped and we were forced to wait for all pressure to be released through the release of the material. The release lasted no more than 15 minutes, with the flow decreasing once the air feed line was disabled.
column169: We have ordered teflon lined steel fittings to attach to railcar flanges to prevent future breakage.  We have also begun research into the design of a portable flange with a safety valve for unloading pressurized railcars.

column168: A crewed BNSF train that was stopped in the rail siding at Monument, CO was alerted by a passing BNSF train crew that they may have an entrained tank car leaking product. The train crew inspected their train and found tank car TCIX 21147 leaking product at the A-end tank head.  BNSF responders applied a magnetic patch over a small corrosion hole that had developed approximately 4 inches below the center point of the tank head. This stopped the flow of product from the corrosion hole by 1030 hrs. MDT, 4/20/2011. The suspected cause of the tank head compromise was an interior liner failure. Responders neutralized spillage that had started to pool under the tank car; and performed ground impact sampling.   Responders began the transfer of product from TCIX 21147 into another suitable tank car that had been positioned on an adjacent track next to TCIX 21147. The product transfer was completed by 2340 hrs MDT, 4/20/2011 without further incident.  Air monitoring was initiated earlier in the day and continued until the product transfer was completed. No air quality issues were noted. In the morning of 4/21/2011, responders removed the applied magnetic patch and sealed the corrosion hole with another temporary patch and secured this patch for movement of TCIX 21147. FRA Verbal Approval 110421R6V was received to move TCIX 21147 from Monument to the BNSF railyard at Denver, CO.  Local authorities initiated an evacuation of approximately 250 households in the Monument area until 2030 hrs MDT, 4/20/2011 with the exception of the nearby households adjacent to the track area where TCIX 21147 was located. The remaining households were allowed back at 2200 hrs. MDT, 4/20/2011. The local school district cancelled classes for the day and an elementary school was used as an evacuation center.     TCIX 21147's side specification stencil indicated that internal lining applied 06/1991, spark tested in the year 2007.

column168: Tank car UTLX 202891 was reported leaking product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area while in the railyard. UTLX 202891 was carefully isolated in the railyard with containment under the leak source area. BNSF responders from mechanical and operating disciplines managed to significantly slow the rate of product release at the BOV. The leak source appeared to be from the BOV mounting flange/tank connection, possibly caused by either a defective mounting flange gasket or a gasket not compatible to the lading inside UTLX 202891. The nearby shipper was contacted and their representative's inspection confirmed the need to transfer product out of UTLX 202891. The shipper arranged to transfer product from UTLX 202891 into tank trucks starting early morning of 4/23/2011. The lading transfer was accomplished without further incident. Afterwards, the product drips ceased. UTLX 202891 is scheduled to be directed to a qualified repair facility once a FRA Movement Approval is received.   No ground impact was observed after responders inspected railyard locations for spillage from UTLX 202891. Any spillage in the containment area or in the track pans evaporated.

It was discovered the shipper did not use the proper inner packaging to comply with the closure instruction of the package manufacturer. There were no inner cartons used, only a large plastic bag. That is inside the outer fiberboard carton there were no inner cartons as required under the package manufacture's " closure instructions" . It was also discoved that on one of the inner bottles the seal was broken, that is the cap may have come off, but the seal between the cap and the bottle was broken and a small amount of contents may have leaked out.   This improper compliance was disovered by the FAA. The shipper was contacted and the shipment refused until the correct and sufficient packaging could be provided.   The FAA is following up with the shipper to ensure the correct " closure instructions" of the package manufacturer are followed.
column169: The shipment was refused andthe shipper advised to use the correct " closure instructions for this packaging..or to use a different packaging system, a stronger outer fiberboard box was recommended. The FAA is following up with the shipper and freight forwarder that the correct " closure instructions " are followed.

column169: USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. Additional dunnage is to be added in like situations in the future.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE LOAD CONTAINING A PALLET OF 8 SULFURIC ACID PLASTIC DRUMS. THE LOAD WAS SECURED WITH SHRINK WRAP. THE SHRINK WRAP WAS HOLDING THE DRUMS TOGETHER. THE LOAD WEIGHED 1,982 POUNDS. THE DRIVER TRANSPORTED THE LOAD TO THE SECOND STOP, WHICH WSAS 20 MINUTES AWAY, WHERE HE NOTED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD FALLEN OFF THE PALLET, SPILLING 4-6 OUNCES OF ACID ONTO THE BED OF TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THIS AREA. THE DRIVER RETURNED TO HYDRITE CHEMICAL, WHERE A HYDRITE EMPLOYEE REMOVED THE PALLET (INCLUDING THE DRUM THAT HAD LEAKED). THEY RELOADED THE TRAILER WITH A DIFFERENT PALLET OF SULFURIC ACID DRUMS. THE TRAILER WAS RETUNED TO GUNVILLE TRUCKING, INC. WHERE IT WAS TREATED WITH AN AGENT TO NEUTRALIZE ANY REMAINING CHEMICAL RESIDUE, AND THEN THE ENTIRE BED WAS PRESSURE WASHED.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING OF DRIVERS IN REGARDS TO CARGO SECURITY, BLOCKING, BRACING AND PROPER STRAPPING PROCEDURES WILL BE PERFORMED. WE WILL PERFORM A UNIT PRESENTATION, PURCHSED FROM J.J. KELLER ON DRIVER AND CARGO SECURITY. THIS UNIT INCLUDES FILM, AN ORAL PRESENTATION AND A TEST. ALL PAST AND FUTURE DRIVERS ARE REQUIRED TO ATTEND TRAINING AFTER WHICH THEY WILL SIGN A TRAINING LOG AND COMPLETE THE WRITTEN TEST. BOTH OF THESE ITEMS WILL THEN BE PLACED IN THEIR PERSONNEL FILE.    DRIVER INSPECTION CHECKLIST    PRE TRIP  -MAKE SURE THAT CARGO IS PROPERLY DISTRIBUTED AND ADEQUATELY SECURED (IN OTHER WORDS, ACCORDING TO THE STANDARD).  -MAKE SURE THAT ALL SECUREMENT EQUIPMENT AND VEHICLE STRUCTURES ARE IN GOOD WORKING ORDER AND USED CONSISTENT WITH THEIR CAPABILITY.  -STOW VEHICLE EQUIPMENT.  -MAKE SURE THAT NOTHING OBSCURES FRONT AND SIDE VIEWS OR INTERFERES WITH THE ABILITY TO DRIVE THE VEHICLE OR RESPOND IN AN EMERGENCY.  -INFORM CARRIER IF PACKAGEING IS NOT ADEQUATE. FOR EXAMPLE:  BANDING IS LOOSE OR NOT SYMMETRICAL ON PACKAGE.  BANDING ATTACHEMENT DEVICE(S) ARE INEFFECIENT.  WRAPPING IS BROKEN OR INEFFCTIVE.  PALLETS ARE BROKEN.    PERIODIC INSPECTIONS DURING TRANSIT  -INSPECT CARGO AND SECURING DEVICES.  -ADJUST CARGO OR LOAD SECUREMENT DEVICES AS NECCESSARY TO ENSURE THAT CARGO CANNONT SHIFT ON OR WITHIN, OR FALL FROM, THE COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE.    AS NECESSARY, ADD MORE SECURING DEVICES.

CAUSE OF DERAILMENT IS BELIEVED TO BE FAILURE OF NORTH TRUCK (TRAILING) A END OF GATX 94662 FUEL OIL TO SWIVEL PROPERLY IN SLIGHT LEFT CURVE HEADING INTO SWITCH SPREADING RAIL ALLOWING SOUTH END LEADING WHEEL (EAST SIDE) OF FOLLOWING CAR GATX 81599 FUEL OIL TO DROP IN. DERAILED CARS BROKE RAIL ON WEST SIDE OF TRACK CAUSING OUTSIDE (WEST SIDE) WHEELS TO TRACK AWAY AND DOWN ALLOWING ARS TO ROLL. DOUBLE SHELF COUPLERS INCREASED SEVERITY OF DERAILMENT PULLING THREE EXTRA CARS ONTO THEIR SIDES. SPEED OF TRAIL 7 MPH. THROTTLE NOTCH 1, IND AND TRAIN BRAKE IN RELEASE POSITION. INSPECTION OF TRUCK AND WHEELS ON GATX 94662 SHOWED NO OBVIOUS FRA DEFECTS. SLIGHT DEVIATION IN CROSS LEVEL OF TRACK AT POINT OF DERAILMENT LESS THAN 1INCH. THIS DEVIATION IS WITHIN FRA SPECS FOR CLASS OF TRACK. TWO FUEL OIL CARS DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM MANWAY COVER AS FOLLOWS: GATX 53838 UNABLE TO STOP SIMILAR LEAK FROM GATX 81599 FUEL OIL WHICH CONTINED DRIPPING UNTIL TANK WAS TRANSLOADED. DRIPPING PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED BY USE OF PADS AND CONTAINERS. CAUSE OF DERAILMENT IS BELIEVED TO BE A COMBINATION OF TRUCK FAILING TO SWIVEL AND ALONG WITH A SLIGHT CROSS LEVEL DEVIATION. TRAIN HANDLING WAS RULED OUT ENTIRELY AS A CONTRIBUTING CAUSE.

column168: 1. AT 19:00 ON 4/20/11 M&ET SWITCH CREW WORKING THE NORTH END OF THE 700 YARD NOTICED THE CAR LEAKING IN TRACK 721 ON THE NORTH END AND REPORTED TO THE M&ET OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR.  2. AT 19:05 M&ET OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR JEFF BRINK REPORTED TO M&ET MANAGER OF SAFETY AND TRAINING RON PETERSON THE LEAK.  3. RON PETERSON ARRIVED AT LEAK LOCATION AT 19:10 AND REQUESTED HAZMAT WAYBILL FROM YARD OFFICE. AT THIS TIME THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING. THE NORTH END OF TH 700 WAS CLOSED TO FURTHER RAIL TRAFFIC. THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE WAY BILL FOR CANUTEC IN CANADA (613-996-6666) WAS USED. CANUTEC HAD NO 24 HOUR NUMBER ON FILE FOR GREENFIELD ONLY A REGULAR HOURS NUMBER. RON PETERSON THEN DIALED THE CHEMTREC NUMBER ON THE RAILCAR 1-800-424-9300 AND CHEMTREC HAD NO INFORMATION. RON PETERSON THEN USED THE GREENFIELD WEB SITE TO CONTACT GREENFIELD ETHANOL INC CHRIS DELINE. CHRIS DELINE EMAILED THE MSDS SHEETS TO M&ET. PHOTOS WERE TAKEN AND A CONTAINMENT POOL WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR IN CASE THERE WAS ANY FURTHER LEAKING THAT NIGHT.  4. STANISLAUS CONSOLIDATED FIRE WAS ADVISED. CALIFORNIA O.E.W. WAS CALLED, CONTROL #11-2519  5. column168: Vehicle was traveling on South on US 231 when the driver veered to the right, leaving the roadway. Evidence at the scene indicated that the driver overcorrected his steering in an attempt to re-enter the roadway. This caused the vehicle to rotate in a counter clockwise motion, resulting in the load (aviation fuel and herbicide) in the cargo tanks to shift. The truck then overturned on its right side and slid across US 231 and collided with a ditch and mailbox. After impact with the ditch the truck then rotated clockwise and came to rest. The truck started leaking through the vent holes and the manhole covers. The crew used absorbent snakes and dry absorbent material to contain the spill and a portable holding tank was brought in to catch the leaking material. The Alabama DOT arrived and shut down the road and began dumping dirt on the spill with a front end loader to help absorb the material. A suction tanker from Eagle SWS arrived and removed the remaining liquid from the tanker. Approximately 300 gallons of Jet A and 1300 gallons of mixed herbicide were removed from the tank. There was originally 325 gallons of jet A and 1500 gal of herbicide mix on the truck prior to the accident. The total spill was estimated at 225 to 250 gallons. The spill entered a ditch approximately 100 feet from the tanker and a DOT employee stated that it was a roadside ditch and did not enter into any flowing water. The tank on the truck was not punctured, leakage occurred through the manhole covers.     The driver of the truck was given a field sobriety test and was arrested for driving under the influence. He later had a BAC of .14%.
column169: This accident was a result of a driver who chose to drive a vehicle while intoxicated. He had been through a treatment program and was given a second chance and obviously was not rehabilitated. Additional training for our supervisors on how to identify drivers who are under the influence of drugs and or alcohol will be conducted.     This incident will be used to train our personnel on how to respond and actions to take in the event this would ever happen again in the future.

column168: THE CONTAINED AREA (DIRT AND GRASS) WAS EXCAVATED AND DISPOSED OF BY EAGLE SWS. SEE ATTACHED DISPOSAL MANIFEST. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE TESTED POSITIVE FOR COCAINE.     VEHICLE 1 WAS TRAVELING WEST ON LA 3127. FOR UNKNOWN REASONS, VEHICLE 1 RAN OFF THE ROAD TO THE RIGHT. IT RETURNED TO ITS LANE OF TRAVEL AND APPLIED THE BRAKES. LEAVING 130 FEET OF SKID MARKS. VEHICLE 1 THEN RAN OFF THE ROAD TO THE FIRHT AND BEGAN TO ROTATE COUNTERCLOCKWISE. IT ENTERED A GRASSY PORTION BEYOND THE WESTBOUND SHOULDER AND BEGAN TO ROLL OVER, LOOSING ITS LOAD OF CHEMICALS FROM ITS BED. VEHICLE 1 ROLLED ONTO ITS DRIVER SIDE AND CAME TO A REST OFF THE ROADWAY FACING EAST.  DRIVER 1 STATED HE WAS WESTBOUND ON LA 3107. AS HE DROVE, IT FELT LIKE ONE OF HIS WHEELS CAME OFF HIS VEHICLE AND HE LOST CONTROL. HE RAN OFF THE ROAD AND FLIPPED OVER. HE LATER STATED TO HIS NURSES AND DOCTOR THAT HE RAN OFF THE ROAD.    I INSPECTED VEHICLE 1 AFTER THE CRASH. VEHICLE HAD ALL ITS TIRES ANS WHEELS IN PLACE NO DEFECTS WERE OBSERVED. THE TOWING COMPANY DEFLATED THE OUTER RIGHT REAR TIRE AS IT WAS RECOVERING THE VEHICLE. THE REAR SUSPENSION (LEAF STRINGS), BOTH LEFT AND RIGHT, WERE BROKEN FROM THE FRAME OF THE VEHICLE. THIS OCCURRED AFTREE THE CARS AS THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER. THE SPRINGS WERE  HANGING ON THE GROUND AS WELL AS THE DRIVESHAFT, WHICH WOULD HAVE LEFT SCRATCHES AND/OR GOUGES IN THE PAVEMENT IF THEY HAD FAILED PRIOR TO THE CRASH. THERE WERE NO MARKS ON THE ROAD OTHER THAN THE SKID MARKS. VEHICLE 1'S SKID MARKS WERE EQUAL IN DISTANCE FROM RIGHT TO LEFT AND NO EVIDENCE OF VEHICLE FAILURE WAS FOUND. VEHICLE 1 WAS TRANSPORTING CHEMICALS WITH PLACARD 1791 CLASS & DISPLAYED FOR HYDROCHOLRIDE. THE CHEMICAL WAS RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THE CRASH AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY CONDUCTED THE CLEANUP. ALCOHOL AND DRUG USE IS NOT CONSIDERED A FACTOR IN THE CRASH, HOWEVER, DRIVER VOLUNTARILY SUBMITTED A BLOOD SAMPLE FOR TESTING. THE TEST RESULTS ARE PENDING.
column169: THE DRIVER HAS RECEIVED ALL OF THE APPROPRIATE TRAINING WILL HAVE COMPLIED WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS REGARDING DRUG TESTING POLICIES AND PROCEDURS. THE DRIVER RECEIVED A DRUG TEST 4 MONTH PRIOR TO THIS ACCIDENT AND PASSED. WE WILL BE WORKING WITH OUR INSURANCE COMPANY TO ADD ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND TESTING COMPANY WIDE.
