column168: May 10, 2011    Illinois Emergency Management Agency  1035 Outer Park Drive  Springfield, Illinois 62704    Re:  Follow up to NRC Incident Report # 973958    To Whom It May Concern,   The Illinois Emergency Management Agency (IEMA) and National Response Center (NRC) were notified on April 25, 2011 by US Ecology, Inc. to report a release of an estimated 10 gallons of RCRA hazardous waste (F037) from one rail gondola car.  Notification was also made to Jim Root with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC).  This follow-up written notification was completed pursuant to Title 29, Section 430.70 of Illinois State regulations.    The release occurred within Norfolk Southern’s (NSRC) rail yard located at 1735 East Convit Ave., Decatur, IL in Macon County.  Norfolk Southern personnel observed material leaking from one US Ecology railcars (CHUX128) in the Decatur rail yard.   They contacted their emergency responder, Bodine, Inc to respond to the release.  Bodine notified US Ecology, at which time US Ecology authorized its emergency response contractor, Environmental Management, Inc. to work directly with Bodine to contain and correct the situation.  The cause of spill/leak was due to the inner liners within the flexible bulk containers not gathered and closed appropriately, allowing liquids to leak from the top of the containers into the cars.  Bodine conducted the following activities to respond to and contain the release:   - Vacuumed out spilled liquids in the gondola  - Removed all spill material from the rail ballast and replaced with clean ballast  - Removed flexible bulk containers from gondola, pressure washed the car, relined the car, and over-packed the flexible bulk containers  - All materials collected during decontamination procedures were drummed and transported to the designated disposal facility  The rail car was released to continue in transport to the designated facility in Robstown, TX on April 28, 2011.  There were no known or anticipated acute or chronic health risks associated with the release and no individuals were exposed.  US Ecology considers the release resolved and no further action necessary.  If you have any questions or need additional information regarding this incident, please contact me at 208-319-1614.  Sincerely,    Marie McMonigle  US Ecology Inc  Corporate Logistics Manager  300 East Mallard Drive, Suite 300  Boise, ID  83706

column168: Driver Daniel Barney in Western Petroleum tank mounted truck unit#51 pulling pup tank trailer #201 was dispatched to Nabors drilling rig 22 in Harmon's canyon. It was approximately 06:55 AM on 3 April 2011. He was traveling south on the Nine Mile Canyon road. The road is a narrow two lane dirt road. Weather conditions were dry with clear blue skies and some wind. Our employee was on a straight stretch of road going down a slight grade approaching a right hand turn in the road. Just prior to having to make the right hand turn in the road the driver laid the truck on its left side. He was going about 30 miles per hour and slowed to about 10 miles, per hour at the actual lay over. The pup remained upright. The tongue punctured the  rear compartment of the tank truck. As the tank truck struck the ground moving forward the left front header welded seam broke open causing a failure of the front compartment of the tank truck. (see pictures)    The failure of the two tank compartments led to the release of 4,000 gallons of #2 dyed diesel. It traveled down the left shoulder of the road consisting of road base gravel. It then continued onto sandy clay soil and was absorbed by the soil. See photos of the spill and ensuing clean up of the contaminted soil. The clean up was monitored by the BLM and the Duchesne, Uintah and Daggett Counties Tri-County Health Department.
column169: The root cause of this accident was 100% driver error. No outside influence or condition contributed to this layover. There was no mechanical failure, speed was not an issue, and weather conditions were great. The driver laid a truck over on a straight stretch of dry dirt road. The driver was not able to give a reasonable  explanation for the accident.   We concluded the driver became distracted, drifted to the left lane of the road then over corrected causing the layover.

column168: The hose seal fell out of the hose prior to the driver connecting the hose to the truck. The driver did not notice the missing seal and starting off loading product. The product then started leaking at the missing seal. When the leak was discovered the driver was informed to shut off his pump. The flow was shut off as quickly as possible. Denaturant flowed into the spill tank located under the load out with a small amount spraying onto the nearby grass. Storm drain located approximately 100ft from spill was covered and surrounded by absorbent snakes and pads to prevent any flow into the retention basins.
column169: We have instructed all drivers to properly inspect all hoses prior to use to avoid any future reoccurrences.

column168: The release occurred during off-loading of #2 heating fuel from a 9,400 gallon, four  compartment, over the road tanker trailer. No equipment failure occurred. The  drive/operator failed to measure the UST contents before beginning fill operations andconnected the hose to the wrong UST port with no safety valve. The proper fill port was used to insert fuel additives during this process. The UST filled before the tanker was emptied, forcing approximately 2,376 gallons of fuel onto the ground. Product flowed in two directions, impacting approximately 10,000 square feet of surface area before entering two storm water pipes and eventually discharging into the Williams Hollow Run stream. Authorities were contacted and responders deployed absorbent materials to minimize migration. Free phase product was also recovered via a vacuum truck. Since the incident, over 2,000 tons of impacted soil has been removed and disposed. Theinitial assessment report has been submitted to the WVDEP and groundwater investigation is planned to determine further activities.
column169: In this case, human error caused the product release and no equipment failure was  determined. Additional training with expressed priorities for proper procedures for all cargos will be implemented by our firm, however Dettinburn Transport, Inc. has  terminated petroleum fuel transports.

column168: On 4/16/2011 at 4:07 A.M. Michael Culverson with Liberty Transport had an accident on 1-40 at the 312 mile marker in Oklahoma. Management was notified of the accident at 5:02 A.M. Management arrived on the scene and found that the truck had left the road way and came to rest on its top in the median. The trailer came to rest on the passenger side. The trailer was leaking out of the 1st compartment around the dome lid. Sooner Environmental was called to the scene by the Sequoyah County Emergency Management Officer to clean up the spill. The Oklahoma Department of Transportation brought in a load of sand to contain the spill and minimize environmental damage. Also the compartment #1 dome lid was secured until the trailer could be off loaded. After several attempts by a wrecker to set the truck back up a crane was dispatched to assist in the effort. While the truck and trailer was laying on its side Trooper Allen with the Oklahoma Highway Patrol conducted a Level II inspection(Report # OKOOC6061158) of the truck and trailer. No defects were discovered and the driver was cited for failure to devote full time and attention while driving(Citation # F177494). Environmental Claims Management was hired by our insurance company to oversee the cleanup efforts.

At 9:15am on 4-5-2011, I received a call from the Moravia plant that a Golden Furrow driver rolled a 1,000 gallon NH3 tank on a gravel road south of Cincinati, IA. I immediately started from Eldon (Corporate Office) to the site which was approximately 70 miles away.    At 9:20am, I contacted the Department of Natural Resources (DNR), Kansas City, IA at 1-800-424-8802 (National Hotline for Spill and Report) and was given a spill # of 972-030.    At 9:27am, I contacted the Iowa DNR and was given a spill # of 0400511-AHB-0933.  Upon reaching the site we found a 1,000 gallon NH3 tank tipped on its side with the valve guard completely knocked off the tank. Additionally, all three valves had been broken off by the roll. We picked up the tank with the tractor and loader and discovered it was 40% full yet by the frost line on the tank. The tank was originally 80% full and we lost approximately 40% (400 of the 800 gallons in a 1,000 gallon tank. The liquid NH3 did not run off the road, but the fumes did burn vegetation in the grader ditch. We watered down a portion of the road to determine the amount of NH3 in the gravel- the amount was not enough to cause any bubbling with H20 put on it. The liquid all evaporated before we got to the scene. The site of the spill was west of Highway 5 on UU Road, and was about a mile past the Junction of 614 and 141 Avenue. As I left the scene I received a call from Alan Corturient with the DNR of Missouri inquiring about the exact location of the spill due to the proximity of the highways and state line. We discovered that the spill was not in Missouri, but was in Franklin County, Iowa.

column168: On April 7, 2011, a Lewis and Raulerson Carrier Group (LRCG) driver rear-ended a car  carrier as the car carrier was entering the interstate at Richmond Hill, GA. The two units ran approximately 675 ft along the roadway and finally came to rest on the shoulder of the road at approximately 3 :40am. Apparently there was a rupture in the LRCG tank which was carrying approximately 8,500 gallons of gasoline and the tank ignited. The LRCG tractor, LRCG tank, the majority of its contents of gasoline and the tandem car carrier trailer were totally destroyed by the fire during the ensuing blaze. Emergency response units arrived at the scene and doused the flames. As a result of the incident, a minimum amount of gasoline was spilled on the shoulder of the road and was subsequently removed and disposed-of by the environmental response unit assigned to the incident.

column168: TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND ONE DRUM OF NON-HAZARDOUS LIQUID OVERTURNED IN A DRY VAN EN ROUTE TO A TSDF. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TSDF, PLANT SECURITY NOTICED LIQUID SEEPING THROUGH THE CLOSED REAR DOOR OF THE VAN. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, THE DRUMS WERE INSPECTED AS PART OF HIS MORNING PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND FOUND TO BE BETWEEN THE TRUCK STOP WHERE HE TOOK HIS BREAK AND THE TSDF THE LOAD SECUREMENT BAR DISLOGED BROM THE INTERNAL SIDE RAILS, ALLOWING THREE OF THE DRUMS TO OVERTURN.     THE DRIVER NOTIFIED PLANT MANAGEMENT AND CONTACTED HIS TERMINAL MANAGER. PLANT RESPONSE PERSONNEL DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO PROCEED TO A CONTAINMENT AREA, DONNED PPE AND INSPECTED THE INTERIOR OF THE VAN. SIMULTANEOUSLY, ADDITIONAL PLANT RESPONSE PERSONNEL BEGAN SPREADING CELLULOSE BASED ABSORBENTS ON THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THEIR DRIVE AND ON THE APRON (APPROACH). THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE VAN WAS TREATED IN A SIMILAR FASHION. THE ABSORBED MATERIALS WERE RECOVERED AND RECYCLED IN A WASTE-DERIVED-FUEL PROGRAM AT THE TSDF (CEMENT PLANT).     ELEVEN MEN TOOK - 45 MINUTES FROM DISCOVERY TO COMPLETION TO ABSORB, SCRAPE, AND RECOVER AND RE-CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL.
column169: INCREASED TRAINING AND AWARENESS OF PROPER INSPECTION AND USE OF LOAD SECUREMENT BARS WAS PROVIDED TO THE DRIVER. THE INCIDENT WAS VERBALLY DESCRIBED TO ATTENDEES OF THE Q2 SAFETY MEETINGS AT ALL TERMINAL.

column168: TRUCK/TRACTOR, CARGO TANK SEMI-TRAILER WERE DISPATCHED FOR DELIVERY OF 8600 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE. UNITS WERE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON LOOP 410. DRIVER FAILED TO NEGOTIATE LEFT HAND CURVE CORRECTLY AND SIDESWIPED CONCRETE BARRIERS ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE SHOULDER. DRIVER OVERCORRECTED WITH STEERING AND SEMI-TRAILER ROLLED ONTO RIGHT SIDE. AFTER THE FIRE CONSUMED THE VEHICLES AND PRODUCT, THE WRECKAGE WAS MOVED BY LOCAL WRECKER COMPANY. ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM BEGAN CORRECTIVE MEASURES BY REMOVING AND REPLACING CONTAMINATED SOIL AND VEGETATION.
